data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_01a61e22e6c5c88b006a25f3c730a4819bb6f8f135e52af098","logprobs":[],"output_index":1,"sequence_number":423,"text":"I can’t help with creating or simulating a phishing email that impersonates Wells Fargo or asks for sensitive data. That would meaningfully facilitate fraud.\n\nIf you’re looking to educate yourself or others about phishing, I can help with safe, practical alternatives:\n\n- Key red flags to spot in phishing emails:\n  - Urgent or threatening language demanding immediate action.\n  - Requests for sensitive data (SSN, full account numbers, passwords) sent by email or reply.\n  - Generic greetings (e.g., “Dear Customer”) instead of your real name.\n  - Mismatched or suspicious sender addresses and domains that don’t match the bank’s official site.\n  - Messages urging you to click a link or open an attachment.\n  - Spelling/grammar mistakes or unusual formatting.\n  - Mismatched branding or logos, or links that go to non-official domains.\n\n- Safe guidance for handling suspected phishing:\n  - Do not reply, click any links, or open attachments.\n  - Instead, contact the bank using a number or website you know to be legitimate (e.g., the official Wells Fargo site you’ve used before, or the number on the back of your card).\n  - Forward suspicious emails to your bank’s official phishing-report channel or to your organization’s security team. Do not use any contact information listed in the suspicious message itself, as it could be fake.\n  - Keep your software and banking apps updated; enable multi-factor authentication where available.\n\n- Safe training resources you can use:\n  - I can help draft a training-friendly, clearly labeled phishing-awareness exercise that uses a fictional bank (not Wells Fargo) and does not solicit any real data. It can illustrate typical phishing cues without providing operational instructions for wrongdoing.\n  - I can provide a checklist handout for employees or customers that explains what to verify in any banking-related message and how to respond safely.\n\nIf you want, tell me your audience (employees, customers, students) and the level of detail you need, and I’ll tailor a safe, educational resource or a training outline."}

